paragraph.docTitle:
Mobilization of storage lipid reserve and expression analysis of lipase and lipoxygenase genes in rice (
Oryza sativa var. Pusa Basmati 1
) bran during germination

subSection.paragraph:
Storage lipid mobilization by lipases and lipoxygenases (LOXs) in response to developmental cues take place during seed germination. After rice grain milling, the endogenous lipases and LOXs present in the bran fraction come in contact with the storage lipid reserve or triacylglycerol (TAG). Lipases catalyze the hydrolysis of TAGs to non-esterified fatty acids (NEFAs) and glycerol. The NEFAs, especially linoleic acid (18:2) produced, are further subjected to oxidative rancidity via peroxidation reaction catalyzed by LOXs. This results in the production of conjugated hydroperoxides of 18:2 that influence the off-flavors in rice bran lipids. The aim of this study is to understand how lipid mobilization and expression of lipase and LOX genes occur in the bran of germinating rice grains (
Oryza sativa var. Pusa Basmati 1
). Our results show that the primary source of storage lipids in bran is TAG, and its mobilization starts at 4 days after imbibition (4 DAI). Using publically available RNA-seq data and phylogeny analyses, we selected a total of 18 lipase and 16 LOX genes in rice for their expression profiles during onset of lipid mobilization. Gene expression analyses revealed OsLip1 , OsLip9 , and OsLip13 ; and OsLOX3 and OsLOX14 as the predominantly expressed genes in bran of germinating rice grains. This study explores two important events in the germinating rice grains, namely, mobilization of storage lipids and expression pattern of lipase and LOX genes. The information generated in this study can be used to efficiently manipulate the genes to enhance the shelf-stability of bran lipid reserve.

Oil-producing crops have been one of the most dynamic parts of agriculture. Worldwide, over the next thirty years, demand for vegetable oils is expected to double, with increasing requirements for food, feed, and fuel. Storage lipids are the major energy reserve stored in the form of triacylglycerols (TAGs) in oil-seed crops including cereals such as rice, oats, barley, and corn. Most of the cereal plants store carbohydrates and proteins in the endosperm; and TAGs and micronutrients in the bran layer, that is further used for oil extraction (
Rondanini et al., 2019
).

Oryza sativa

(rice) belongs to the family 
Poaceae
and is an important cereal crop due to the high starch content in endosperm along with lipids (3–4% of the grain), stored in the bran (Juliano and Tuano, 2019). Rice bran consists of a pericarp, seed coat, nucellus, and aleurone layer, the latter being high in TAGs, proteins, vitamins, and mineral content (
Gul et al., 2015
). TAGs stored in the rice bran are rich in palmitic (16:0), oleic (18:1), and linoleic (18:2) acids, that are also found in the rice bran oil (RBO) (
Goffman et al., 2003
; 
Burlando and Cornara, 2014
).

TAGs are accumulated rapidly in rice grains between 5 and 12 days after pollination (
DAP
) (
Ichihara et al., 2003
) and stored as oil bodies (OBs) that are coated by oleosin proteins (oleosin 16 and oleosin 18) (
Chuang et al., 1996
). During germination of rice grains, TAGs stored in bran are degraded by TAG lipases, releasing non-esterified FAs (NEFAs) and glycerol. The NEFAs are further degraded through the β- oxidation and glyoxylate pathway, and subsequently converted to transportable nutrient molecules (sugars) that are transferred through the absorptive scutellum to furnish energy for the growing embryo (
Graham, 2008
).

In rice bran, compartmentalized TAGs are stored as OBs in the aleurone layer of bran fraction. However, during the rice milling individual cells are disrupted, thus exposing the TAG reserve to highly reactive endogenous lipases. This enables lipases to catalyze the hydrolysis of TAGs resulting in the release of NEFAs. This hydrolytic activity tends to continue during the prolonged storage of milled bran, reaching up to 40–60% of NEFAs (
Dunford, 2019
). The liberated NEFAs, especially the 18:2, is further subjected to oxidative degradation catalyzed by LOX enzymes resulting in the production of hydroperoxides of 18:2 (
Viswanath et al., 2020
). These hydroperoxide molecules are the key metabolites responsible for the off-flavors of rice bran lipids (
Malekian et al., 2000
).

In order to study the mobilization of lipid reserves of bran in germinating rice grains, the four major lipid contents viz., TAGs, DAGs, NEFAs, and polar lipids (PLs) were analyzed between 2 h after imbibition (HAI) and 8 days after imbibition (DAI). The difference between the initial TAGs at 2 HAI and the remaining TAGs at 8 DAI was measured to indicate the TAG mobilization in rice bran. To begin with the TAG pool (
Fig. 1a
), it was observed that the abundance of TAGs in the rice bran tissue remained nearly unaltered between 2 HAI (58.0 μmol/g) and 4 DAI (54.4 μmol/g). Mobilization of TAG pool during germination of rice grain started at 4 DAI, as it was observed that at 6 DAI and 8 DAI, the TAG content declined to 36.2 μmol/g and 20.4 μmol/g, respectively (
Fig. 1a
). Compared with the TAG pool, other lipid classes (DAGs, NEFAs, and PLs) were found to be present in very low quantities in the bran fraction. The DAG pool of bran also showed a decline from 2 HAI (5.3 μmol/g) to 8 DAI (1.8 μmol/g), indicating that majority of the DAG pool was mobilized during this period (
Fig. 1a
). A relatively low mobilization pattern was observed for PLs, that showed a decline in its abundance from 2 HAI (7.2 μmol/g) to 8 DAI (5.1 μmol/g) (
Fig. 1a
). However, an increase in NEFA pool was observed from 2 HAI (0.4 μmol/ g) to 8 DAI (6.9 μmol/g).

In order to obtain a holistic view of the lipid reserve mobilization events occurring in bran during different stages of rice grain germination, FA profiles of four bran lipid classes viz., TAGs, DAGs, NEFAs and PLs were also investigated (
Fig. 1b–e
). The FA profiles of the bran lipids consisted of three major FAs, 16:0, 18:1, and 18:2 along with other minor FAs, 16:1 (palmitoleic acid), 18:0 (stearic acid), 18:3 (α- linolenic acid), 20:0 (eicosanoic acid), and 20:1 (
cis
-11-eicosenoic acid). As expected 16:0, 18:1, and 18:2 FA of the TAG reserve showed a sharp decline between 4 DAI to 8 DAI from 10.5–4.3 μmol/g, 24.8–8.2 μmol/g and 14.0–5.9 μmol/g, respectively. In case of the DAG pool, 16:0 FA declined from 2.5 μmol/g at 2 HAI to 0.7 μmol/g at 8 DAI, but remained unchanged or slightly changed for other FAs during early germination (
Fig. 1c
). The NEFA pool showed an increasing proportion of 16:0, 18:1, and 18:2 FAs from 0.2–3.36 μmol/g, 0.07–1.27 μmol/g and 0.05–1.49 μmol/g, respectively from 2 HAI to 8 DAI (
Fig. 1d
), while the other FAs remained nearly unchanged. FAs of the PL pool started to accumulate in the bran tissues from 4 DAI onwards. The 16:0 and 18:1 FAs of PL pool were noted to accumulate from 0.76–1.28 μmol/g and 0.28–1.66 μmol/ g, respectively from 4 DAI to 8 DAI (
Fig. 1e
).

In order to identify the rice lipase and LOX genes for this study, data mining was performed using the Rice Genome Annotation Project (
RGAP
) public database. A query for the keyword “Lipase” in the putative function search tool resulted in a catalogue of 73 lipase genes (Table S3). Due to the large number of putative lipases obtained from the search, we grouped them based on their fragments per kilo base per million mapped reads (
FPKM
) expression. A maximum of five genes with highest 
FPKM
values in each of the four selected stages of the following tissues, viz., developing rice grain (5 and 10 
DAP
), endosperm (25 
DAP
) and leaves (20 
DAP
) were chosen for our study. After eliminating the duplicate gene entries from the shortlisted 20 genes, 11 lipases were selected for further analysis (
Table 1
). We would like to mention here that out of these 11 genes obtained from 
RGAP
data mining process, four genes were found to be devoid of lipase active site (
Table 1
). We studied their relative abundances in rice bran during the germination and postgermination stages.

To reveal the conserved motifs that were identical among lipase and LOX protein sequences, structural motif annotation was performed. Primarily, 20 motifs were predicted in the rice lipase and LOX proteins (
Fig. 5
). OsLip1, OsLip2, OsLip9, and OsLip13 shared six motifs (motif-1- 6), OsLip-3 and OsLip15 shared seven motifs (motif-3, 7, 9, 14, 16, 18, and 20), OsLip4 and OsLip18 shared seven motifs (3, 11–13, 15, 17, and 20), and OsLip12 and OsLip17 shared three motifs (motif-8, 10, and 19) (
Fig. 5a
). None of the above 20 motifs were found in OsLip10 and OsLip14 protein sequences.

On the other hand, OsLOX1-2, 4–5, 7, and 11–14 shared twenty identical motifs (motifs 1–20; 
Fig. 5b
). OsLOX3 and OsLOX9 consisted of eighteen and seventeen motifs, respectively (
Fig. 5b
). OsLOX6, 10, and 15–16 proteins consisted of different motif organization patterns compared to other LOXs. This observation suggesting functional similarities among lipase and LOX proteins within the same subfamily sharing the similar conserved motifs.

To investigate the expression of 18 lipase genes in developing seeds (5 and 10 
DAP
), endosperm (25 
DAP
), and leaves (20 
DAP
), RNA-seq transcriptome data (obtained from 
RGAP
) in the form of differentially expressed values were analyzed (
Table 1
). Among the 18 lipase genes observed during rice grain development, 
OsLip8
(44.0 
FPKM
) and 
OsLip16
(63.1 
FPKM
), were observed to be the highly expressed lipase genes based on the 
FPKM
values. Similarly, in the case of endosperm, 
OsLip16
(152.9 
FPKM
) and 
OsLip11
(116.8 
FPKM
) were found to be highly expressed.

The standard practice of bran layer separation disrupts the physical barriers that sequester the cellular lipases and LOXs away from the lipids stored in bran. This, in turn, induces rapid hydrolysis of the bran lipids to high NEFAs. Several efforts have been made to reduce the rancidity and increase the shelf-life of lipids by adapting the pre-milling and postharvesting techniques. However, these techniques have negative impact on the quality of the bran micronutrients (
Amarasinghe et al., 2009
). Little attention was paid in understanding the causative genes responsible for the hydrolytic and oxidative rancidity of the bran lipids. Thus, it is imperative to target lipase and LOX genes in the grain to improve the quality of bran lipid with lower rancidity and longer shelf-life. The present study was aimed to fill this research gap and to unveil the process of TAG mobilization in rice bran during grain germination along with expression analysis of the lipase and LOX genes.

Storage lipid breakdown during seed germination starts with the hydrolysis of TAG reserves (
Borek et al., 2015
). In rice, 0–4 DAI is considered as the germination stage and 5–10 DAI as post-germinative growth (
Vijayakumar and Gowda, 2012
). Mobilization of the TAG pool in the rice bran started at 4 DAI (
Fig. 1a
). However, degradation of TAGs did not coincide with the NEFA pool accumulated in bran tissues (
Fig. 1d
). The above discrepancy may be due to the catabolism of NEFAs through β- oxidation or amino acid biosynthesis pathway (
Graham, 2008
; 
Borek and Ratajczak, 2010
). Meanwhile, a large proportion of the total DAGs were also utilized from 2 HAI to post-germinative growth at 8 DAI (
Fig. 1c
). On the other hand, the PL content remained mostly unaltered during the mobilization of TAGs and DAGs.

Of the four lipid classes, 16:0, 18:1, and 18:2 are the three predominant FAs detected during germination and post-germinative growth (
Fig. 1b–e
). In TAGs, the contents of 16:0, 18:1, and 18:2 FAs decreased drastically from 4 DAI onward whereas, the NEFA content in the bran started to increase at the onset of 2 DAI (
Fig. 1c
). Although the accumulation of NEFAs started early, the loss of FAs from the TAG fraction was relatively much higher than the amount of NEFAs accumulated in the bran. The FA composition of 16:0, 18:1, and 18: 
2 in
the bran PL pool increased from 4 to 8 DAI (
Fig. 1d
). These results are in agreement with those reported earlier in germinating seeds (
Shrestha et al., 2016
).

document.paragraph:
The exon/intron organization of rice lipase and LOX genes was identified using gene structure display server (GSDS 2.0) by sequence alignment of the coding sequence with their corresponding genomic DNA sequences (
Hu et al., 2015
). Conserved motif annotation of lipase and LOX genes was performed using the multiple EM for motif elicitation (MEME) suite (
Bailey et al., 2006
). The maximum number of motifs screened was set at 20.

subSection.paragraph:
According to 
Bhunia et al. (2016)
, rice grain dissected bran tissues (~ 
50 mg
) were used to extract the total lipid content. To determine the TAG, DAG, NEFA and PL content along with the FA composition of individual lipid classes, total bran lipids were extracted in chloroform: methanol (2:1, v/v) for 2 h at room temperature. To remove the polar fraction of the total lipid extract, it was treated with 0.88% (w/v) potassium chloride. The lower organic phase was collected in a fresh glass tube, concentrated in a Rotavapor R-300 (BUCHI, 
Germany
) and separated through thin layer chromatography (TLC) with a solvent system of hexane: diethyl ether: acetic acid (70:30:1, v/v). Individual lipid classes were exposed with iodine (CDH, 
India
) vapors to visualize the spots. Separated spots of individual lipid classes were scratched out from the TLC, eluted with chloroform and concentrated in a Rotavapor.

Acid-catalyzed FA methyl esters (FAMEs) were prepared from the individual lipids using 4% (v/v) sulfuric acid in methanol (freshly prepared) along with 0.2 ml toluene (CDH, 
India
) and 10 μg of heptadecanoic acid (17:0, Sigma, 
USA
) as an internal standard. Transesterification reaction was carried out at 80 
◦
C for 2 h, followed by extraction of FAMEs with 4 ml of Hexane (CDH, 
India
) and 1 ml of 0.9% (w/v) of sodium chloride solution. The non-polar upper phase was collected and concentrated in the Rotavapor.

Bran tissues were scraped from the imbibed rice grain using a sterile scalpel and placed at 80 
◦
C for long term-storage. The pooled bran samples were divided into three sub-pooled samples to extract RNA. Samples were then crushed in liquid nitrogen using mortar and pestle, and used to isolate total RNA using Spectrum plant total RNA extraction kit (Sigma-Aldrich, 
USA
). RNase-free DNase treatment (New 
England
Biolabs, MA, 
USA
) was employed to remove any residual contamination of genomic DNA using the manufacturer’ s protocol. Quantification and integrity of total RNA were examined using NanoDrop One microvolume UV–Vis spectrophotometer (Thermo Fisher Scientific, MA, 
USA
) and 1% agarose gel electrophoresis, respectively. First-strand cDNA was synthesized from 1 μg of total RNA extracted from the bran using iScript reverse transcription supermix (Bio-Rad, 
USA
) in a total reaction volume of 20 μl.
